**Part II - Structural Testing and Mocking**



**Exercise 1.**

        Here verification of the number of times certain methods from other classes are called is all that can be done. Using the last parseMap() method from the MapParser class will go through all of the other parseMap() methods, so using this method will check the functionality of all the others as well.

        Tests are implemented in the test/java/nl/tudelft/jpacman/level/MapParserTest class.



**Exercise 2.**

**       ** Bad weather cases are caught if:
1. The file to read from is not present;

2. The list of strings to read from is null;

3. The list of strings to read from is empty;

4. The first element of the list of strings to read from is an empty string;

5. The list of strings to read from have different lengths of the strings;

6. A string from the list of strings contains a forbidden character.

        These tests are also implemented in the class from exercise 1.



**Exercise 3.**

        The coverage we achieved is 100% branch coverage. The tests are implemented in the test/java/nl/tudelft/jpacman/game/GameUnitTest class. They consist of:
1. There is an alive player and there are positive number of pellets left;

2. There is an alive player and there are no remaining pellets;

3. There is not an alive player and it does not matter the number of pellets (since the if-statement will already have evaluated to false).

4. Invoke the start method 2 times to check if it is actually not possible to start a second game.

**Exercises 5. and 6.**

        An abstract class called CollisionMapTest was created in which all the tests for both PlayerCollision and DefaultPlayerInteractionMap classes are implemented. They are run from the derived classes PlayerCollisionsTest and DefaultPlayerInteractionMapTest, in which only the initial set up for the tests is implemented.

        All of these tests are located in the test/java/nl/tudelft/jpacman/level package.



**Exercise 7.**

**       ** Coverage of PlayerCollisions class went from 66% (which was covered from the smoke test at the beginning) up to 85%. The only branch which is not covered is when the first unit is neither a player, nor a ghost, nor a pellet. This is totally fine since if this is tested it would probably cause bugs in the future if other units are added to the game - probably their collisions would not be the same, so they would not be covered by only one test of the class they extend from.
        The DefaultPlayerInteractionMap was not tested at all in the beginning because it is not used in the application. There 100% line coverage is achieved from our test.



**Exercise 8.**

**       ** Usage of new Random() should be avoided. Instead, it should be made to be injectable in the constructor of the class. In this way the testability of the class will raise and the method invoked with the parameter can be mocked and forced to return a certain value. With this the problem of different outputs is fixed and the method can be tested easily.



**Exercise 9.**

smokeTest() can be flaky because the player doesn&#39;t move for 0.5 seconds in the  test case. During this time only the ghosts are moving. However, even though not likely, the player might still be alive after these 0.5 seconds.

Flaky tests are often labeled as non-deterministic, due to the fact that a test can either pass or fail for the exact same configuration. To find the reasons behind flaky tests it requires a lot of practice but there are some common opinions why a test could be flaky such as concurrency, third-party systems (such as databases or Web APIs), infrastructure problems, clean up state, etcâ€¦



**Exercise 10.**

**       ** Achieving 100% code coverage means that all aspects of the application are tested which is really good. However, it also has its bad sides. A lot of people start trying to achieve 100% code coverage without even thinking what tests they are creating (and usually those tests end up being really simple, thus inefficient when searching for a bug). This is called &quot;Treating the metric&quot; and it definitely should be avoided. When tests are designed the quality of the tests is of great importance and testers should focus on that.



**Exercise 11.**

**       ** Mocks are really useful when trying to execute unit tests. However, their main drawback is that they basically are not real and integration problems might not be found. They help when testing the functionality of one unit of the application, but after that integration testing for the interaction between the different units of the application is mandatory.

**Exercise 12.**

        The test suite might end up being slow because of calls to a database, Web API or other business logic. In order to make them faster, these dependencies should be mocked. However, after this integration tests should be done in order to see if the interaction between the units works as expected.



**Exercise 13.**

**       ** Mocking is used to make tests simpler and more readable. If a class does not depend on any other classes, databases, etc. mocking probably is not needed as it will only make the tests more complicated. Mocks also should not be used when performing integration testing - there the interaction between different components of the application is tested and thus one component should not be &quot;told&quot; what to give to the other one.



**Exercise 14.**

        There are a total of 4 vulnerabilities:

1. While playing at some point you start losing points, and in the end you might even end up with a negative score;
2. While playing, the application throws an exception without any reason;
3. From time to time the player dies without colliding with a ghost (so basically with no reason);
4. At some point, while still having a positive score, when consuming a pellet the score drastically drops to a really big negative number.



**Exercise 15.**

        As expected, the Default Point Calculator works properly:

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

The player does around 760 moves before a ghost kills him and the score and consumed pellets are proportional, which means that no strange behavior is observed.

However, the Amazing Point Calculator shows some anomalies:



 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

In this figure we can observe 2 anomalies:
        1. Instead of increasing, the score decreases from a certain point of time - it is caused by the following if-statement:

if (this.pelettesEaten \&gt;= 28 &amp;&amp; player.getScore() \&gt; 0) {

   player.addPoints(-15);

}

        2. PacMan dies without colliding with a ghost. This is triggered by the following condition:

else {

   if (this.pelettesEaten \&gt; 34) {

       player.setAlive(false);

   }



 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

        From this graph we can observe that the score just drops to a negative value at certain points. This is caused by an overflow, since the score of the player is saved as a variable of type int. If a really big number is added to this score it will overflow and thus cause the score to become negative. It is triggered by the following if-statement:

if (player.getDirection() == Direction.WEST &amp;&amp; this.pelettesEaten \&gt;= 15) {

   player.addPoints(2147483647);

}



 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

        From this test case we can see that in the end PacMan is still alive. However, according to the JavaDoc for the JPacmanFuzzer test class, PacMan should be dead in the end. This means that something else caused the application to stop. The only reasonable explanation would be that it was an exception, triggered by the following condition:

if (this.pelettesEaten \&gt; 34 &amp;&amp; player.getDirection() == Direction.NORTH) {

   throw new RuntimeException(&quot;Relax! You found one of the solutions!&quot;);

}



**Exercise 16.**

        The static analysis didn&#39;t give any problems. The reason is that SpotBugs does not detect dynamic class loading.

        The vulnerability that applies to this code is Insecure Direct Object Reference. The &quot;scorecalc.properties&quot; file is referenced directly. If a malicious user gets access to it they can manipulate this file to get unauthorized data. Thus, we either should avoid direct reference or provide more security.





**Exercise 17.**

The following steps should be taken into account when security problems occurs during dynamic loading of a class.

- -- **Security Manager** :  is an object that defines a security policy for an application which decides if actions are unsafe or sensitive.
- -- **ClassLoader** : any instance of it can define classes with arbitrary security permissions.
- -- **Separate JVM :** so if one of the processes fails or it&#39;s security is weak, the others don&#39;t get affected.
